  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT159-kilavi">1. talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi ceṟippaṟivuṟuttatu.
            2. uyir cela vēṟṟu varaivu variṉum atu māṟṟuṭaṟku nikaḻttatūumām.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">1. The confidante informing of confinement, while HE is behind the hedge.
            2. Undertaken, even when another marriage comes while live passes,  to prevent that. (TP 109, l.14)</p>
          </div>


        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT159">
<l>                taḻaiyaṇi yalku ṟāṅkal cellā</l>
<l>                nuḻaiciṟu nucuppiṟ kevva māka</l>
<l>                vammel lāka niṟaiya vīṅkik</l>
<l>                kommai varimulai ceppuṭa ṉetiriṉa</l>
<l>                yāṅkā kuvaḷkol pūṅkuḻai yeṉṉu</l>
<l>                mavala neñcamō ṭucāvāk</l>
<l>                kavalai mākkaṭṭip pētai yūrē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
           <l>This foolish village has scandal[-spreading] people</l>
           <l>who do not inquire after afflicted hearts:<note place="foot">What is the function of the construction <term xml:lang="ta">cāvu + -oṭu</term> (cf. KT 145.4)? It might be understood either like above as an indirect object, or also to be connected with the <term xml:lang="ta">mākkaḷ</term>: "distressed people who do not inquire, with afflicted hearts: ...".</note></l>
           <l>[she with the] flower earring, what will become of her?</l>
           <l>– round-shaped breasts, surpassing pots,<note place="foot">How do we have to understand the construction and content of <term xml:lang="ta">ceppuṭaṉ etiriṉa</term>? In any case this n.pl. needs a subject, which cannot but be <term xml:lang="ta">mulai</term>. Cām. glosses with <term xml:lang="ta">ceppoṭu māṟupaṭṭaṉa</term> "at variance with pots", presumably in the sense of the Sanskrit topos of breasts competing with pots for their shape and extension.</note></l>
           <l rend="indent">fully<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">niṟaiya</term>: is this infinitive to be understood adverbially?</note> swollen the pretty soft bosom,<note place="foot">What is the difference between mulai and ākam? Does the former refer to the actual breasts and the latter to the bosom?</note></l>
           <l rend="indent">while the leaf-adorned hips, unbearably,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tāṅkal cellā</term> is to be taken adverbially; cf. KT 265.1, 287.4, 340.4 for the construction of verbal noun plus <term xml:lang="ta">cellā(tu)</term>. Moreover <term xml:lang="ta">cel</term> might have the function of an auxiliary: "not arrived at bearing". Srin. suggests understanding <term xml:lang="ta">cel</term> as "to be suitable, acceptable".</note></l>
           <l rend="indent">become troublesome to the narrow small waist?</l>


            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
